description: From Middle English *rykke, from Old English hrycce (“rick, heap, pile”), cognate with Scots ruk (“rick”), Norwegian ruka (“rick, haystack”). Related also to Old English hrēac (“rick, stack”), from Proto-Germanic *hraukaz (“heap”). Further relations: Dutch rook, Norwegian rauk, Swedish rök, Icelandic hraukur.

entries.meaning: Straw, hay etc. stored in a stack for winter fodder, commonly protected with thatch.
examples: There is a remnant still of last year's golden clusters of beehive ricks, rising at intervals beyond the hedgerows; […].

entries.meaning: (US) A stack of wood, especially cut to a regular length; also used as a measure of wood, typically four by eight feet.

verbs.description: rick (third-person singular simple present ricks, present participle ricking, simple past and past participle ricked)

entries.meaning: To heap up (hay, etc.) in ricks.

description: From earlier wrick, from Middle English wricken, wrikken (“to move back and forth”), probably from Middle Dutch *verwricken or Middle Low German vorwricken. Cognate with West Frisian wrikke, wrikje, Dutch wrikken, Low German wricken, German wricken, Danish vrikke, Swedish vricka.

verbs.description: rick (third-person singular simple present ricks, present participle ricking, simple past and past participle ricked)

entries.meaning: To slightly sprain or strain the neck, back, ankle etc.
(military, derogatory and demeaning) A brand new (naive) boot camp inductee.
examples: No turning back now rick, you are the property of the US government now.
